Looking at relationship between Year and Visitation

ggplot(national_parks_data, aes(x = YearRaw, y = Visitors, group = 1)) +
  geom_line() +
  geom_point() +
  labs(title = "Number of Visitors by Year",
       x = "Year",
       y = "Number of Visitors") +
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45, hjust = 1))
## Warning: Removed 4 rows containing missing values (`geom_point()`).

#table of visitors by year
visitors_by_year <- national_parks_data %>%
  group_by(YearRaw) %>%
  summarise(total_visitors = sum(Visitors))

# Print the table
print(visitors_by_year)

Parks by State

library(knitr)

parks_per_state <- national_parks_data %>%
  group_by(State) %>%
  summarise(number_of_parks = n())

# Create a bar plot
ggplot(parks_per_state, aes(x = State, y = number_of_parks)) +
  geom_bar(stat = "identity", fill = "skyblue") +

Most and Least Popular Parks based on Visitation per year

park_visitation <- national_parks_data %>%
  group_by(State, Unit.Name, YearRaw ) %>%
  summarise(total_visitation = sum(Visitors, na.rm = TRUE), .groups = 'drop') 

# Find the park with the most visitation per year
most_visitation_park <- park_visitation %>%
  group_by(YearRaw) %>%
  filter(total_visitation == max(total_visitation))

# Find the park with the least visitation per year
least_visitation_park <- park_visitation %>%
  group_by(YearRaw) %>%
  filter(total_visitation == min(total_visitation))

# Print the results
print(most_visitation_park)

Park with most and least total visitation

park_visitation <- national_parks_data %>%
  group_by(Unit.Name) %>%
  summarise(total_visitation = sum(Visitors, na.rm = TRUE), .groups = 'drop')

# Find the park with the most total visitation
most_visitation_park <- park_visitation %>%
  filter(total_visitation == max(total_visitation))

#and least
least_visitation_park <- park_visitation %>%
  filter(total_visitation == min(total_visitation))

# Print the result
print(most_visitation_park)

Region and Visitation

# Load necessary libraries
library(stats)

# Perform ANOVA to check if Region affects park visitation
model <- aov(Visitors ~ Region, data = national_parks_data)

# Print the ANOVA table
print(summary(model))
##                Df    Sum Sq   Mean Sq F value Pr(>F)    
## Region          7 4.146e+16 5.923e+15   42.38 <2e-16 ***
## Residuals   21548 3.012e+18 1.398e+14                   
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1
## 4 observations deleted due to missingness
#test says visitation is different based on Region

#Plot Visitors by region
ggplot(national_parks_data, aes(x = Region, y = Visitors)) +
  geom_bar(stat = "summary", fun = "sum", fill = "skyblue") +
  labs(title = "Visitation by Region",
       x = "Region",
       y = "Total Visitation")
## Warning: Removed 4 rows containing non-finite values (`stat_summary()`).

#Region with most visitors: PW
#Region with least visitors: AK
